WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:11.310 --> 00:00:14.070
We are all apes.

00:00:14.070 --> 00:00:15.540
All of you are apes--

00:00:15.540 --> 00:00:17.495
every single one of you.

00:00:17.495 --> 00:00:18.870
If we look in the
animal kingdom,

00:00:18.870 --> 00:00:24.180
our closest living relatives
are chimpanzees, bonobos,

00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:26.100
and gorillas.

00:00:26.100 --> 00:00:28.850
So here's one of my cousins.

00:00:28.850 --> 00:00:30.930
We look very different.

00:00:30.930 --> 00:00:35.060
So when did our family trees
split apart from each other?

00:00:35.060 --> 00:00:36.920
What makes him a gorilla?

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:38.885
What makes me a human?

00:00:41.625 --> 00:00:44.571
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:01:01.265 --> 00:01:04.211
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:09.180 --> 00:01:11.560
This is Albert the gorilla.

00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:12.870
I'm Professor Alice Roberts.

00:01:12.870 --> 00:01:16.500
Welcome to the second of
this year's Royal Institution

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:18.120
Christmas Lectures.

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:21.150
Now, Albert is going to come
and say hello to some of you.

00:01:21.150 --> 00:01:22.740
He's very interested in you.

00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:25.420
I'm sure you're
interested in him as well.

00:01:25.420 --> 00:01:27.300
On the surface, he
looks really different.

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:29.310
But maybe when you
get a bit closer,

00:01:29.310 --> 00:01:31.350
you can see some similarities.

00:01:31.350 --> 00:01:33.180
If you hold up your hand--

00:01:35.823 --> 00:01:37.740
he's looking right at
you there in the hoodie.

00:01:37.740 --> 00:01:40.500
If you hold up your hand,
he should hold up his hand

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:41.670
as well.

00:01:41.670 --> 00:01:43.290
And you can compare
your hand to his.

00:01:43.290 --> 00:01:45.040
You can see that his
hand's very large.

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:47.010
But he's got four
fingers and a thumb.

00:01:47.010 --> 00:01:48.510
He's got fingernails.

00:01:48.510 --> 00:01:49.650
Try smiling at him.

00:01:49.650 --> 00:01:51.570
Show your teeth.

00:01:51.570 --> 00:01:53.460
He'll recognise that as a smile.

00:01:53.460 --> 00:01:55.200
He knows that you're
being submissive.

00:01:55.200 --> 00:01:56.525
He's baring his teeth as well.

00:01:56.525 --> 00:01:57.650
I think he quite likes you.

00:01:57.650 --> 00:01:58.770
Do you want to say, hello?

00:01:58.770 --> 00:01:59.952
Hello.

00:01:59.952 --> 00:02:01.115
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:01.115 --> 00:02:01.740
It's all right.

00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:03.270
He's harmless.

00:02:03.270 --> 00:02:04.620
He does like you.

00:02:04.620 --> 00:02:06.240
Oh.

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:07.530
He's found a friend--

00:02:07.530 --> 00:02:09.389
a cousin and a friend.

00:02:09.389 --> 00:02:11.190
Albert, come back
down here though.

00:02:11.190 --> 00:02:12.210
Come on.

00:02:12.210 --> 00:02:14.320
Come down

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:16.300
Albert is a great ape.

00:02:16.300 --> 00:02:19.230
We're part of this family
of great apes as well.

00:02:19.230 --> 00:02:23.920
And so those great apes include
gorillas and chimpanzees

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:27.400
and bonobos and orangutans.

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:29.050
And then our family
of great apes

00:02:29.050 --> 00:02:32.830
is part of an even bigger group
of animals called primates.

00:02:32.830 --> 00:02:36.200
And all primates have
various things in common.

00:02:36.200 --> 00:02:41.890
So [LAUGHS] we're all
very good with our hands.

00:02:41.890 --> 00:02:44.080
We've got grasping hands.

00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:45.550
All primates have clavicles.

00:02:45.550 --> 00:02:47.050
You've got collarbones,
haven't you?

00:02:47.050 --> 00:02:49.810
There's one thing that
makes you a primate.

00:02:49.810 --> 00:02:53.230
And also, all primates
are really, really good

00:02:53.230 --> 00:02:54.388
at climbing.

00:02:54.388 --> 00:02:57.874
[AUDIO OUT]

00:03:51.658 --> 00:03:55.144
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:05.850
Alex and Dane, that
was absolutely amazing.

00:04:05.850 --> 00:04:08.130
How wonderful to
see people who can

00:04:08.130 --> 00:04:11.160
use their bodies in
that way and move around

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:13.350
in 3D space like that.

00:04:13.350 --> 00:04:18.269
It reminds us just how flexible
the human body really is.

00:04:18.269 --> 00:04:20.790
I think a lot of us move
around in a really boring way

00:04:20.790 --> 00:04:22.050
in comparison.

00:04:22.050 --> 00:04:24.630
Which one of you
here has ever tried

00:04:24.630 --> 00:04:27.500
to climb a climbing
frame or a tree?

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:29.520
You've all done it.

00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:32.130
So we are primates at heart.

00:04:32.130 --> 00:04:33.510
Thank you very much.

00:04:33.510 --> 00:04:36.463
And Alex and Dane, what
an amazing performance.

00:04:36.463 --> 00:04:38.130
I thought you were
absolutely brilliant.

00:04:38.130 --> 00:04:40.240
Let's ask Albert what he thinks.

00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:44.139
What do you think, Albert,
to their parkour performance?

00:04:44.139 --> 00:04:45.410
[GRUNTS]

00:04:45.410 --> 00:04:47.910
Aww.

00:04:47.910 --> 00:04:50.370
Oh, I think it was
better than that.

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:51.210
Oh well.

00:04:51.210 --> 00:04:53.830
A big round of applause
for our great ape.

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:57.330
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:01.830 --> 00:05:04.170
Alex and Dane showed
just brilliantly

00:05:04.170 --> 00:05:07.160
how we can still move
around in 3D space

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:11.610
as primates do if we want
to and if we train at it.

00:05:11.610 --> 00:05:13.070
But in fact, there
are other clues

00:05:13.070 --> 00:05:14.830
to our primate connections.

00:05:14.830 --> 00:05:17.220
And there's one clear one
I'd like to show you now,

00:05:17.220 --> 00:05:19.820
which is only there for a
fleeting moment in our lives

00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:21.500
when we're very, very young.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:24.260
So I'd like you to do a very
gentle round of applause

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:27.110
now for Vicki and Aria.

00:05:27.110 --> 00:05:29.360
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:30.210
Hello, Vicki.

00:05:30.210 --> 00:05:30.710
Hello.

00:05:30.710 --> 00:05:32.260
Hello, Aria.

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:34.030
So Aria is very, very small.

00:05:34.030 --> 00:05:35.770
She's a very new person.

00:05:35.770 --> 00:05:36.860
How old is she?

00:05:36.860 --> 00:05:37.720
She's six weeks.

00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:38.510
She's six weeks?

00:05:38.510 --> 00:05:39.060
Yes.

00:05:39.060 --> 00:05:39.850
You're gorgeous.

00:05:39.850 --> 00:05:41.270
Aren't you lovely?

00:05:41.270 --> 00:05:43.870
Now, Aria is so
small that she still

00:05:43.870 --> 00:05:47.430
has a reflex that all of
you will have lost long ago.

00:05:47.430 --> 00:05:49.270
But I might be able
to show it to you.

00:05:49.270 --> 00:05:50.290
I want to at her hand.

00:05:50.290 --> 00:05:50.740
Is this all right, Vicki?

00:05:50.740 --> 00:05:51.430
Yes, of course.

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:55.240
And what I'm trying to do is
put my finger in her hand.

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:57.420
And she closes her fingers.

00:05:57.420 --> 00:05:57.950
[CRYING]

00:05:57.950 --> 00:05:58.783
She doesn't like it.

00:05:58.783 --> 00:06:00.190
Oh, no, Aria.

00:06:00.190 --> 00:06:01.280
I'm sorry, poppet.

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:02.245
[CRYING]

00:06:02.245 --> 00:06:02.745
Oh.

00:06:02.745 --> 00:06:03.330
It's OK.

00:06:03.330 --> 00:06:04.130
Oh.

00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:07.690
She's really gripping my
finger really strongly.

00:06:07.690 --> 00:06:11.560
She's got this incredible
reflex which is elicited.

00:06:11.560 --> 00:06:14.020
I'm making it happen just by
slightly tickling the palm

00:06:14.020 --> 00:06:15.850
of her hand, and she grabs on.

00:06:15.850 --> 00:06:17.161
[CRYING]

00:06:17.161 --> 00:06:17.905
Oh, baby.

00:06:17.905 --> 00:06:19.160
Good girl.

00:06:19.160 --> 00:06:23.120
So this reflex disappears
by about six months of age.

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:24.980
But it's something
that we think is

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:28.610
leftover from our ancient
primate ancestors.

00:06:28.610 --> 00:06:31.460
And Vicki and Aria,
I've got a little video

00:06:31.460 --> 00:06:33.840
here to show you some cousins.

00:06:33.840 --> 00:06:35.550
So these are chimpanzees.

00:06:35.550 --> 00:06:37.700
And what you can see
here is a chimpanzee baby

00:06:37.700 --> 00:06:39.130
on its mother's back.

00:06:39.130 --> 00:06:41.870
And you can see how the
mum's moving pretty swiftly.

00:06:41.870 --> 00:06:43.670
And that chimp baby,
even though it's tiny,

00:06:43.670 --> 00:06:45.530
has to cling on for dear life.

00:06:45.530 --> 00:06:47.720
So it's really gripping
with its hands.

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:49.880
So this is where we think
this grasp reflex is

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:52.090
leftover from in our babies.

00:06:52.090 --> 00:06:55.078
But by about six months, she'll
have forgotten how to do it.

00:06:55.078 --> 00:06:56.120
Thank you so much, Vicki.

00:06:56.120 --> 00:06:56.620
Thank you.

00:06:56.620 --> 00:06:57.590
Thank you, Aria.

00:06:57.590 --> 00:06:59.260
Another gentle
round of applause.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:06:59.840
Thank you.

00:06:59.840 --> 00:07:01.768
[APPLAUSE]

00:07:01.768 --> 00:07:06.350
So we've seen now evidence of
primate connections in the way

00:07:06.350 --> 00:07:09.320
that we can move with
our bodies if we want to.

00:07:09.320 --> 00:07:13.040
We've seen primate connections
in this amazing grasp reflex

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:15.920
that we're all born
with but then lose.

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:18.920
And there are other signs
of these connections

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:20.150
when we look at anatomy.

00:07:20.150 --> 00:07:21.380
I'm an anatomist.

00:07:21.380 --> 00:07:23.240
So I go under the skin
and I start looking

00:07:23.240 --> 00:07:25.140
at the structure of the body.

00:07:25.140 --> 00:07:26.750
And what I've got
here are two bones

00:07:26.750 --> 00:07:29.270
from two different species.

00:07:29.270 --> 00:07:32.420
One of them is from a
human, and one of them

00:07:32.420 --> 00:07:34.430
is from a chimpanzee.

00:07:34.430 --> 00:07:37.700
First of all, there's this
very, very narrow groove

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:38.925
at the top of this bone.

00:07:38.925 --> 00:07:40.550
If we look at the
bottoms of the bones,

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:42.008
there are some
differences as well.

00:07:42.008 --> 00:07:45.270
So both of these bones have
got a ball shape at the bottom.

00:07:45.270 --> 00:07:47.720
And on this bone, you can
see that there's a much more

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:49.550
prominent lip on it.

00:07:49.550 --> 00:07:51.230
So there are really
subtle differences

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:55.400
that tell me that this bone
is the chimpanzee humerus,

00:07:55.400 --> 00:07:58.130
and this one is a human humerus.

00:07:58.130 --> 00:08:00.280
But they're kind of
shockingly similar.

00:08:00.280 --> 00:08:01.940
Now, we're going to
put them in context

00:08:01.940 --> 00:08:04.400
and bring in two
complete skeletons--

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:08.520
a human skeleton and
a chimpanzee skeleton.

00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:10.520
And when you look at a
whole skeleton like this,

00:08:10.520 --> 00:08:11.937
I think you notice
the differences

00:08:11.937 --> 00:08:14.270
more than the similarities
at first, especially

00:08:14.270 --> 00:08:17.160
because the human has
been hung like this,

00:08:17.160 --> 00:08:19.402
so he looks like he's
walking on two feet.

00:08:19.402 --> 00:08:21.110
And the chimpanzee is
arranged like this,

00:08:21.110 --> 00:08:22.280
so he looks like
he's just getting

00:08:22.280 --> 00:08:23.697
ready to go knuckle
walking, which

00:08:23.697 --> 00:08:26.210
is what chimpanzees tend
to do when they drop down

00:08:26.210 --> 00:08:27.500
to the ground.

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:29.450
So that was the humerus
that we were looking

00:08:29.450 --> 00:08:30.650
at in both of these animals.

00:08:30.650 --> 00:08:33.372
That's a very similar bone
in the chimp and the human.

00:08:33.372 --> 00:08:35.580
There are other bones, which
are much more different.

00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:37.640
So if you look at
the pelvis here,

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:39.140
that's a completely
different shape.

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:43.039
It's got a very
long, flat blade.

00:08:43.039 --> 00:08:44.870
Whereas our pelvis
is kind of a basin

00:08:44.870 --> 00:08:48.380
shape, and it's adapted to us
walking upright on two legs.

00:08:48.380 --> 00:08:50.810
But there are other bits
that are quite similar still.

00:08:50.810 --> 00:08:54.090
And our hands is a
great example of that.

00:08:54.090 --> 00:08:56.840
So we'll hold up the chimp
hand and the human hand.

00:08:56.840 --> 00:08:59.180
You can see that the chimp
thumb is a bit weedy compared

00:08:59.180 --> 00:09:00.530
to the human thumb.

00:09:00.530 --> 00:09:03.890
But still, base of those hands
are capable of doing something

00:09:03.890 --> 00:09:05.390
that you can all do.

00:09:05.390 --> 00:09:08.180
Those thumbs can move
in a very special way.

00:09:08.180 --> 00:09:10.070
The thumb can move
right across the palm,

00:09:10.070 --> 00:09:12.740
and you can touch
the tip of your thumb

00:09:12.740 --> 00:09:14.240
to your little finger.

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:17.230
It may not feel like a really
special thing to be able to do.

00:09:17.230 --> 00:09:21.650
But this opposable thumb is
really important in grasping.

00:09:21.650 --> 00:09:24.070
It's something that other
primates have as well.

00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:27.170
But our opposable
thumbs are exceptional.

00:09:27.170 --> 00:09:31.310
So they're really great when
you're making and using tools.

00:09:31.310 --> 00:09:33.620
But I want to demonstrate
just how useful they

00:09:33.620 --> 00:09:35.660
are with two volunteers.

00:09:35.660 --> 00:09:39.080
So can I have two volunteers
from the audience, please?

00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:43.880
So I'd like you in the
mustard jumper and, yes,

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:45.350
in the grey hoodie.

00:09:45.350 --> 00:09:45.980
Come down.

00:09:45.980 --> 00:09:46.820
Come down.

00:09:46.820 --> 00:09:49.190
And we've got a little
challenge for you.

00:09:49.190 --> 00:09:51.110
As you can see, it
involves grapes.

00:09:51.110 --> 00:09:52.040
What's your name?

00:09:52.040 --> 00:09:52.760
Esme.

00:09:52.760 --> 00:09:53.260
Esme.

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:54.980
So you're there with
the green grapes, Esme.

00:09:54.980 --> 00:09:56.188
Are you right or left handed?

00:09:56.188 --> 00:09:56.938
I am right-handed.

00:09:56.938 --> 00:09:57.438
OK.

00:09:57.438 --> 00:09:59.330
Can you put your left
hand behind your back?

00:09:59.330 --> 00:10:00.260
Lovely.

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:01.340
And what's your name?

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:01.890
Lena.

00:10:01.890 --> 00:10:02.720
Lena.

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:05.960
So Esme and Lena,
you're going to be

00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:10.240
pitted against each other in
a grape picking challenge.

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:11.470
You're both right-handed.

00:10:11.470 --> 00:10:13.790
So Lena, if you put your
left hand behind your back

00:10:13.790 --> 00:10:16.370
as well so you're not
tempted to use it at all.

00:10:16.370 --> 00:10:18.740
What I want you to
do, when I say go,

00:10:18.740 --> 00:10:22.280
is pluck grapes from that
bunch just using one hand.

00:10:22.280 --> 00:10:24.290
And put the grapes
in this empty bowl.

00:10:24.290 --> 00:10:25.740
So that's the challenge.

00:10:25.740 --> 00:10:26.240
All right?

00:10:26.240 --> 00:10:27.640
So taking grapes off--

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:29.390
I'll put the bowls
around that way for you

00:10:29.390 --> 00:10:30.470
as well, as it might
be a bit easier.

00:10:30.470 --> 00:10:31.373
Thank you.

00:10:31.373 --> 00:10:32.540
So you pluck the grapes off.

00:10:32.540 --> 00:10:33.710
You put them in the bowl.

00:10:33.710 --> 00:10:35.960
And you've got 15
seconds to do it.

00:10:35.960 --> 00:10:37.940
I'm going to give
you a countdown--

00:10:37.940 --> 00:10:43.250
1, 2, 3, 4, I
declare a thumb war.

00:10:43.250 --> 00:10:44.055
Go!

00:10:44.055 --> 00:10:44.910
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:10:44.910 --> 00:10:45.854
15 seconds.

00:10:50.580 --> 00:10:51.980
Who's going to do
better at this?

00:10:51.980 --> 00:10:52.480
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:53.820
I think that might be cheating.

00:10:53.820 --> 00:10:55.240
[LAUGHS]

00:10:59.026 --> 00:11:02.490
All right, stop--
stop, stop, stop.

00:11:02.490 --> 00:11:04.350
Drop the grapes.

00:11:04.350 --> 00:11:06.600
Now, the really amazing thing
about this demonstration

00:11:06.600 --> 00:11:08.250
is it's meant to show
how, if you don't

00:11:08.250 --> 00:11:11.940
have your opposable
thumb, you're

00:11:11.940 --> 00:11:13.470
much worse at plucking grapes.

00:11:13.470 --> 00:11:14.070
Do you know what, Lena?

00:11:14.070 --> 00:11:15.870
We've done it with so
many people this afternoon

00:11:15.870 --> 00:11:17.520
in rehearsals, and
we always ended up

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:19.230
with a great pile
of grapes over here

00:11:19.230 --> 00:11:20.980
and a very small pile
of grapes over here.

00:11:20.980 --> 00:11:21.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:21.810 --> 00:11:24.210
I think possibly you cheated
by picking up the bunch

00:11:24.210 --> 00:11:25.406
and shaking it.

00:11:25.406 --> 00:11:27.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:27.420 --> 00:11:31.170
But this does show
something really important.

00:11:31.170 --> 00:11:33.180
So if you don't pick up
the bunch and shake it,

00:11:33.180 --> 00:11:35.570
then you're going to end up
with fewer grapes in here.

00:11:35.570 --> 00:11:38.370
Humans are also rather
ingenious and very good

00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:39.590
at problem solving.

00:11:39.590 --> 00:11:43.710
So thank you very much to
Lena and Esme for testing out

00:11:43.710 --> 00:11:44.400
their thumbs.

00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:45.636
Thank you.

00:11:45.636 --> 00:11:48.552
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:49.542 --> 00:11:51.000
So lots of things,
then, that we've

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.090
got in common with
our primate cousins--

00:11:54.090 --> 00:11:56.370
anatomy, behaviour.

00:11:56.370 --> 00:11:59.040
But actually these
