00:21:34.080 --> 00:21:35.920
by holding onto other things.

00:21:35.920 --> 00:21:37.800
And as we've seen
with the orangutan,

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:39.660
other apes do this as well.

00:21:39.660 --> 00:21:43.380
So what we think happened
deep back in our ancestry--

00:21:43.380 --> 00:21:46.530
oh, hello-- what we
think happened deep back

00:21:46.530 --> 00:21:51.060
in our ancestry is that our
ancient tree-living ancestors

00:21:51.060 --> 00:21:53.538
were doing this, were
walking around in trees.

00:21:53.538 --> 00:21:55.830
And then, when they started
walking on the ground more,

00:21:55.830 --> 00:21:57.330
it was quite a
simple thing for them

00:21:57.330 --> 00:22:00.600
to do to drop out of the
tree and just continue

00:22:00.600 --> 00:22:05.400
walking on two legs, on
two feet on the ground.

00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:07.200
So we don't have
to explain how you

00:22:07.200 --> 00:22:11.280
go from being a four-legged
quadrupedal animal to being

00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:12.690
an upright animal.

00:22:12.690 --> 00:22:14.940
We think our ancestors
always were upright.

00:22:14.940 --> 00:22:17.040
And then they just swapped
walking in the trees

00:22:17.040 --> 00:22:19.620
for walking on the ground.

00:22:19.620 --> 00:22:24.300
And then, by the time we get to
about 4 to 3 million years ago,

00:22:24.300 --> 00:22:26.760
we find ancestors
who have started

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:30.300
to adapt in their bodies to
this new way of getting around.

00:22:30.300 --> 00:22:32.250
So their skeletons
have started to change.

00:22:32.250 --> 00:22:35.160
So they're getting better
and better at walking.

00:22:35.160 --> 00:22:38.310
And I want to introduce you
to one of these ancestors.

00:22:38.310 --> 00:22:43.410
So this is a reconstruction
of the fossil of a very, very

00:22:43.410 --> 00:22:45.210
famous fossil discovery.

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:46.890
She's called Lucy.

00:22:46.890 --> 00:22:50.340
And she was discovered
in Ethiopia.

00:22:50.340 --> 00:22:55.740
She belongs to a species called
Australopithecus afarensis.

00:22:55.740 --> 00:22:57.900
Australopithecus
means "southern ape."

00:22:57.900 --> 00:23:00.630
And afarensis means
she comes from the Afar

00:23:00.630 --> 00:23:02.670
Region of Ethiopia.

00:23:02.670 --> 00:23:05.020
And this is a
reconstruction of Lucy here.

00:23:05.020 --> 00:23:08.430
Se we can imagine what she would
have looked like in the flesh.

00:23:08.430 --> 00:23:11.670
So we can see from her skeleton
that she's got adaptations

00:23:11.670 --> 00:23:13.140
to walking on two legs.

00:23:13.140 --> 00:23:14.550
Her pelvis has changed.

00:23:14.550 --> 00:23:17.580
It's become adapted
to bipedalism--

00:23:17.580 --> 00:23:19.010
to two-legged walking.

00:23:19.010 --> 00:23:22.530
Her femur-- her thigh bone-- is
curving in to bring her knees

00:23:22.530 --> 00:23:26.190
and her feet underneath
her centre of mass.

00:23:26.190 --> 00:23:28.560
She's still got some
adaptations to climbing

00:23:28.560 --> 00:23:32.760
left in her skeleton, though,
including quite curved finger

00:23:32.760 --> 00:23:33.600
bones.

00:23:33.600 --> 00:23:35.308
And we're not quite
sure if she was still

00:23:35.308 --> 00:23:37.860
doing a lot of climbing,
or whether these are just

00:23:37.860 --> 00:23:40.650
leftover from her ancestors.

00:23:40.650 --> 00:23:42.928
But she's quite small.

00:23:42.928 --> 00:23:44.970
There are some other
individuals from her species

00:23:44.970 --> 00:23:46.813
who are a bit bigger than her.

00:23:46.813 --> 00:23:49.230
But there's something else
that's quite striking, I think,

00:23:49.230 --> 00:23:50.820
about her limb proportions.

00:23:50.820 --> 00:23:53.310
She's got longish
arms and short legs.

00:23:53.310 --> 00:23:55.550
So she doesn't really
look like us, yet.

00:23:55.550 --> 00:23:57.450
And there's a
change to long legs

00:23:57.450 --> 00:23:59.820
that happens about
2 million years ago

00:23:59.820 --> 00:24:03.060
with a new species appearing.

00:24:03.060 --> 00:24:06.530
And this species is
called Homo erectus.

00:24:06.530 --> 00:24:09.910
And Homo erectus appears
about 2 million years ago.

00:24:09.910 --> 00:24:12.450
This particular reconstruction
is based on a fossil

00:24:12.450 --> 00:24:14.550
for 1 and 1/2 million years ago.

00:24:14.550 --> 00:24:18.330
And he's called Nariokotome Boy,
because his fossilised remains

00:24:18.330 --> 00:24:23.080
were found near the
Nariokotome River in Kenya.

00:24:23.080 --> 00:24:25.370
And he's quite interesting
when you look at his bones,

00:24:25.370 --> 00:24:27.740
because he looks like he's 15.

00:24:27.740 --> 00:24:30.180
Have we got any 15-year-olds
in the audience tonight?

00:24:30.180 --> 00:24:31.880
If I were to do an X-ray,
and look at your bones,

00:24:31.880 --> 00:24:33.590
I'd see that some of
your bones would--

00:24:33.590 --> 00:24:35.000
still had gaps at the ends.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:37.520
They haven't fused yet,
because you're still growing.

00:24:37.520 --> 00:24:39.200
And his skeleton
looks a bit like that.

00:24:39.200 --> 00:24:40.910
But you're nearly fully grown.

00:24:40.910 --> 00:24:43.460
So he's got the skeleton
of a 15-year-old,

00:24:43.460 --> 00:24:44.655
almost fully grown.

00:24:44.655 --> 00:24:47.030
But then if we look carefully
at his bones and his teeth,

00:24:47.030 --> 00:24:49.610
it turns out that he was only 8.

00:24:49.610 --> 00:24:52.610
So he was only 8, but with
the body of a 15-year-old.

00:24:52.610 --> 00:24:56.240
He grew up really, really fast.

00:24:56.240 --> 00:25:00.740
He didn't have the long
childhoods that we have.

00:25:00.740 --> 00:25:03.176
And those childhoods
are really important--

00:25:03.176 --> 00:25:04.850
important to us as humans.

00:25:04.850 --> 00:25:09.390
They allow us time to learn
before we grow up into adults.

00:25:09.390 --> 00:25:11.360
We can see other
things in his skeleton.

00:25:11.360 --> 00:25:14.270
In his back here, he's
got strong back muscles.

00:25:14.270 --> 00:25:15.953
And then, moving
down to his legs,

00:25:15.953 --> 00:25:17.120
he's got strong leg muscles.

00:25:17.120 --> 00:25:19.100
And he's got really
springy tendons--

00:25:19.100 --> 00:25:21.320
particularly this one
here-- the Achilles tendon

00:25:21.320 --> 00:25:22.880
that attaches at the heel.

00:25:22.880 --> 00:25:26.180
We can see from the bones
that he had a really lovely

00:25:26.180 --> 00:25:28.160
big springy Achilles tendon.

00:25:28.160 --> 00:25:30.770
And that's why we've
reconstructed him like this.

00:25:30.770 --> 00:25:34.910
Because we think Nariokotome
Boy was a runner.

00:25:34.910 --> 00:25:37.760
But in order to see just
how good the human body is

00:25:37.760 --> 00:25:40.470
at running, we're going
to look at it in action.

00:25:40.470 --> 00:25:44.630
And Aoife is in the
library with a runner.

00:25:44.630 --> 00:25:45.290
Hi, Alice.

00:25:45.290 --> 00:25:46.550
Yeah, I'm here in the library.

00:25:46.550 --> 00:25:49.220
And I'm with Marcus from
Sheffield Hallam University,

00:25:49.220 --> 00:25:52.327
and also our very
wonderful volunteer Tom,

00:25:52.327 --> 00:25:54.410
who's been running here
on the treadmill for quite

00:25:54.410 --> 00:25:55.280
a few minutes.

00:25:55.280 --> 00:25:58.500
So Marcus, you've been
capturing his movements.

00:25:58.500 --> 00:25:59.680
Yeah, exactly.

00:25:59.680 --> 00:26:02.030
So you might see that
Tom's covered in all

00:26:02.030 --> 00:26:04.310
of these spherical markers.

00:26:04.310 --> 00:26:07.050
And what we can do, we can use
these motion capture cameras

00:26:07.050 --> 00:26:10.050
that you can see dotted
around in the red cameras.

00:26:10.050 --> 00:26:11.990
And they can really
accurately measure

00:26:11.990 --> 00:26:13.630
the position of those markers.

00:26:13.630 --> 00:26:16.850
Yeah, and we see his head
is staying quite steady.

00:26:16.850 --> 00:26:18.830
And we also see
that his shoulders

00:26:18.830 --> 00:26:21.200
are moving back and forth.

00:26:21.200 --> 00:26:22.760
So motion capture
is a technology,

00:26:22.760 --> 00:26:25.640
which people like Marcus,
who is a sport scientist,

00:26:25.640 --> 00:26:29.240
can use to analyse how
the human body moves,

00:26:29.240 --> 00:26:32.600
but also to help athletes
improve their performance.

00:26:32.600 --> 00:26:36.200
And we can see, looking at that
little stick man there of Tom,

00:26:36.200 --> 00:26:37.820
his shoulders are moving.

00:26:37.820 --> 00:26:40.360
So by the point in time
we've got Nariokotome Boy,

00:26:40.360 --> 00:26:41.920
we've got a nice, low waist.

00:26:41.920 --> 00:26:44.048
And that enables your
shoulders to rotate.

00:26:44.048 --> 00:26:45.590
And that helps you
to balance, and it

00:26:45.590 --> 00:26:47.630
makes running more efficient.

00:26:47.630 --> 00:26:50.660
And we've also got his
head staying quite still.

00:26:50.660 --> 00:26:53.090
So like Nariokotome Boy, he's
got nice, strong muscles,

00:26:53.090 --> 00:26:55.280
and that strong ligament
in the back of the head,

00:26:55.280 --> 00:26:57.818
and strong back muscles to
stop his body pitching forward.

00:26:57.818 --> 00:26:59.360
Because actually
when you're running,

00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:02.020
you're pretty much falling
over almost at every step,

00:27:02.020 --> 00:27:04.410
and you've got to stop
yourself doing that.

00:27:04.410 --> 00:27:06.962
So we're seeing these
adaptations in action.

00:27:06.962 --> 00:27:08.420
But actually there's
something else

00:27:08.420 --> 00:27:13.070
that would stop you in
your tracks with running.

00:27:13.070 --> 00:27:15.390
And I think, Aoife, you're
measuring that as well.

00:27:15.390 --> 00:27:15.890
Yeah.

00:27:15.890 --> 00:27:18.080
So Tom is a pretty
wonderful volunteer,

00:27:18.080 --> 00:27:21.140
because he has also
swallowed one of these.

00:27:21.140 --> 00:27:23.300
This is a really
small thermometer.

00:27:23.300 --> 00:27:26.150
And he was asked to do
this by Doctor Danny

00:27:26.150 --> 00:27:28.010
Longman from Cambridge
University, who's

00:27:28.010 --> 00:27:29.210
also joining us here.

00:27:29.210 --> 00:27:30.750
So what have you been measuring?

00:27:30.750 --> 00:27:31.250
Sure.

00:27:31.250 --> 00:27:33.040
So the pill that Tom
swallowed earlier

00:27:33.040 --> 00:27:36.020
is transmitting data
wirelessly to this laptop here.

00:27:36.020 --> 00:27:38.570
And that's giving us information
about Tom's deep core body

00:27:38.570 --> 00:27:40.970
temperature, letting us
know how warm he really is.

00:27:40.970 --> 00:27:42.380
And what do you see here?

00:27:42.380 --> 00:27:44.750
So we've got a graph
of his temperature.

00:27:44.750 --> 00:27:46.280
We do indeed.

00:27:46.280 --> 00:27:48.980
So we see here at rest, Tom
had a core body temperature

00:27:48.980 --> 00:27:52.160
of 37 degrees, which is
that of a healthy human.

00:27:52.160 --> 00:27:54.410
However, when he started
to run, about here,

00:27:54.410 --> 00:27:56.660
we see that his core body
temperature started to rise.

00:27:56.660 --> 00:27:58.880
And that was because his
muscles were activated.

00:27:58.880 --> 00:28:01.493
And muscle activation
generates a lot of heat.

00:28:01.493 --> 00:28:02.910
He looks quite
hot, I have to say.

00:28:02.910 --> 00:28:03.830
He does indeed.

00:28:03.830 --> 00:28:06.320
So when Tom started to warm
up, his evolved heat-loss

00:28:06.320 --> 00:28:08.090
mechanisms began to kick in.

00:28:08.090 --> 00:28:10.040
And he was able to lose
heat at the same rate

00:28:10.040 --> 00:28:11.840
as his muscles were
producing them.

00:28:11.840 --> 00:28:14.028
And we can see here, we
actually get a plateau

00:28:14.028 --> 00:28:15.070
in core body temperature.

00:28:15.070 --> 00:28:15.570
Yeah.

00:28:15.570 --> 00:28:17.510
And is this the same
then for other animals?

00:28:17.510 --> 00:28:20.360
Well, if we were to have
a gazelle or a cheetah

00:28:20.360 --> 00:28:22.160
during this experiment
in place of Tom,

00:28:22.160 --> 00:28:23.952
we would see that the
core body temperature

00:28:23.952 --> 00:28:25.238
would continue to increase.

00:28:25.238 --> 00:28:27.530
They don't have the mechanisms
to lose heat that we do.

00:28:27.530 --> 00:28:29.870
So a cheetah would have to
stop despite being so fast.

00:28:29.870 --> 00:28:30.370
Absolutely.

00:28:30.370 --> 00:28:30.870
Yeah, yeah.

00:28:30.870 --> 00:28:33.860
So Tom here is
better than a tomcat.

00:28:33.860 --> 00:28:36.650
So there's obviously something
that our bodies are doing

00:28:36.650 --> 00:28:38.690
in order to regulate
that temperature,

00:28:38.690 --> 00:28:41.960
and to try to keep us cool
whilst everything we're doing

00:28:41.960 --> 00:28:45.085
is trying to make us hotter
and hotter and hotter.

00:28:45.085 --> 00:28:46.460
And the amazing
thing about being

00:28:46.460 --> 00:28:48.560
able to regulate our
temperature like this is it

00:28:48.560 --> 00:28:50.280
means we can just
carry on running.

00:28:50.280 --> 00:28:52.250
We're really good at
endurance running.

00:28:52.250 --> 00:28:55.610
We can even outrun
horses and dogs.

00:28:55.610 --> 00:28:57.668
And there's a particular
secret to how we do it.

00:28:57.668 --> 00:28:58.710
That was good, wasn't it?

00:28:58.710 --> 00:29:00.270
And Aoife, you
happen to be back--

00:29:00.270 --> 00:29:00.770
Oh, yeah.

00:29:00.770 --> 00:29:01.590
--in the theatre.

00:29:01.590 --> 00:29:02.300
Uh-huh.

00:29:02.300 --> 00:29:05.360
So you're going to
demonstrate for me, Aoife--

00:29:05.360 --> 00:29:06.110
Yeah.

00:29:06.110 --> 00:29:07.690
--what our superpower is.

00:29:07.690 --> 00:29:09.590
How we manage to keep
our temperature down.

00:29:09.590 --> 00:29:10.670
Yeah.

00:29:10.670 --> 00:29:11.450
There's a spike.

00:29:11.450 --> 00:29:12.052
Uh-huh.

00:29:12.052 --> 00:29:13.260
And we've got these balloons.

00:29:13.260 --> 00:29:14.468
And we've got these balloons.

00:29:14.468 --> 00:29:17.460
So this balloon represents
the amount of sweat

00:29:17.460 --> 00:29:23.550
that a 70-kilogramme dog sweats
out during an hour of exercise.

00:29:23.550 --> 00:29:25.130
70 kilogrammes is
bigger than me.

00:29:25.130 --> 00:29:25.630
Yeah.

00:29:25.630 --> 00:29:26.170
Its quite a big dog.

00:29:26.170 --> 00:29:26.820
That's a big dog.

00:29:26.820 --> 00:29:27.280
Yeah.

00:29:27.280 --> 00:29:28.600
I'm going to go and
stand over here.

00:29:28.600 --> 00:29:29.100
OK.

00:29:29.100 --> 00:29:30.730
You're making me worried, Alice.

00:29:30.730 --> 00:29:33.310
I'm wearing my good shoes.

00:29:33.310 --> 00:29:33.978
OK.

00:29:33.978 --> 00:29:35.020
Well, I need a countdown.

00:29:35.020 --> 00:29:36.228
I'm not doing this by myself.

00:29:36.228 --> 00:29:36.970
OK?

00:29:36.970 --> 00:29:39.528
3, 2, 1!

00:29:39.528 --> 00:29:40.504
[POP]

00:29:40.504 --> 00:29:41.970
[SHRIEK]

00:29:41.970 --> 00:29:42.860
OK.

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:43.360
OK.

00:29:43.360 --> 00:29:44.870
So it wasn't as
bad as I expected.

00:29:44.870 --> 00:29:45.300
So that's a 70-kilogramme--

00:29:45.300 --> 00:29:46.570
No, it's not too bad, is it?

00:29:46.570 --> 00:29:48.020
That was a 70-kilogramme dog.

00:29:48.020 --> 00:29:49.145
Dogs don't sweat that much.

00:29:49.145 --> 00:29:51.770
They have to stop, and they had
to bring their temperature down

00:29:51.770 --> 00:29:53.330
by panting.

00:29:53.330 --> 00:29:55.160
But humans sweat quite a bit.

00:29:55.160 --> 00:29:59.120
So this balloon contains
the amount of sweat

00:29:59.120 --> 00:30:03.270
that a human sweats out
during an hour of exercise.

00:30:03.270 --> 00:30:04.900
So we probably need
a countdown again.

00:30:04.900 --> 00:30:07.560
3, 2, 1!

00:30:07.560 --> 00:30:08.550
[POP]

00:30:08.550 --> 00:30:10.550
[SHRIEK]

00:30:10.550 --> 00:30:11.770
That was two litres.

00:30:11.770 --> 00:30:12.480
Oh, yeah.

00:30:12.480 --> 00:30:13.880
Two litres of sweat.

00:30:13.880 --> 00:30:14.980
I think I felt it.

00:30:14.980 --> 00:30:15.730
Yeah.

00:30:15.730 --> 00:30:16.610
Are you a bit wet?

00:30:16.610 --> 00:30:17.720
I'm a bit wet now, yeah.

00:30:17.720 --> 00:30:18.440
I'm sorry, Aoife.

00:30:18.440 --> 00:30:19.550
You're not really
sorry, though, are you?

00:30:19.550 --> 00:30:19.940
Not really.

00:30:19.940 --> 00:30:20.440
No.

00:30:20.440 --> 00:30:21.200
Not really.

00:30:21.200 --> 00:30:23.270
So Aoife has magnificently--

00:30:23.270 --> 00:30:24.320
I'm so sorry, Aoife.

00:30:24.320 --> 00:30:26.660
She's going to get me back
now in lecture 3, isn't she?

00:30:26.660 --> 00:30:28.910
She's going to be thinking
of something to do to me.

00:30:28.910 --> 00:30:31.040
Aoife's demonstrated
brilliantly,

00:30:31.040 --> 00:30:34.280
I thought-- absolutely
brilliantly-- the secret

00:30:34.280 --> 00:30:35.570
of sweat.

00:30:35.570 --> 00:30:38.720
This is how we humans manage
to keep our temperature down.

00:30:38.720 --> 00:30:41.510
And there's something about
us that's very, very different

00:30:41.510 --> 00:30:43.820
from our closest
living ape relatives,

00:30:43.820 --> 00:30:45.320
and that is it looks
as though we've

00:30:45.320 --> 00:30:47.940
lost the fur over our bodies.

00:30:47.940 --> 00:30:50.810
In fact, that's not quite
true, because over the surface

00:30:50.810 --> 00:30:54.170
of the human body we've got
5 million hair follicles.

00:30:54.170 --> 00:30:56.750
And that's actually the
same as a chimpanzee has.

00:30:56.750 --> 00:31:00.215
It's just that our hairs are
so much finer over our bodies.

00:31:00.215 --> 00:31:02.090
And that's really
important, because it means

00:31:02.090 --> 00:31:03.860
those hairs don't trap sweat.

00:31:03.860 --> 00:31:06.950
The sweat spreads out on
the surface of the skin,

00:31:06.950 --> 00:31:08.770
and then it can evaporate off.

00:31:08.770 --> 00:31:12.170
And as it evaporates off
it takes heat with it.

00:31:12.170 --> 00:31:15.350
So we're really, really
good at sweating.

00:31:15.350 --> 00:31:18.510
And so we're able to
run long distances.

00:31:18.510 --> 00:31:20.870
And we think this was
incredibly important

00:31:20.870 --> 00:31:24.610
to our ancient ancestors--
people like Nariokotome Boy.

00:31:24.610 --> 00:31:27.390
So going back 2
million years ago,

00:31:27.390 --> 00:31:30.200
we've got the expansion
of grasslands in Africa--

00:31:30.200 --> 00:31:31.310
savanna.

00:31:31.310 --> 00:31:33.890
And with the expansion
of these grasslands

00:31:33.890 --> 00:31:35.480
we've got the expansion
of populations

00:31:35.480 --> 00:31:38.690
of animals who are eating
that grass-- so, grazers.

00:31:38.690 --> 00:31:41.690
And then the predators
are eating the grazers.

00:31:41.690 --> 00:31:45.020
And if you could run
fast, and get to a carcass

00:31:45.020 --> 00:31:46.970
that a predator had taken down--

00:31:46.970 --> 00:31:49.880
perhaps those lions have gone
off to sleep in the shade--

00:31:49.880 --> 00:31:51.710
you can steal some of that meat.

00:31:51.710 --> 00:31:53.660
So our ancestors were
certainly scavenging.

00:31:53.660 --> 00:31:55.500
They may have been
hunting as well.

00:31:55.500 --> 00:31:58.370
And we also know that they were
making stone tools that can

00:31:58.370 --> 00:32:01.190
cut through flesh and sinew.

00:32:01.190 --> 00:32:05.090
And now I want to introduce
to you two people who

00:32:05.090 --> 00:32:07.070
make stone tools today.

00:32:07.070 --> 00:32:09.500
And they make stone tools
that are very much like those

00:32:09.500 --> 00:32:10.790
of our ancestors--

00:32:10.790 --> 00:32:14.060
Antony and Nada, from the
Ancient Technology Centre

00:32:14.060 --> 00:32:15.410
in Dorset.

00:32:15.410 --> 00:32:16.968
Let's give them a
round of applause.

00:32:16.968 --> 00:32:20.720
[APPLAUSE]

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:24.670
Now before they get started,
some very sharp flakes

00:32:24.670 --> 00:32:25.510
can fly from this.

00:32:25.510 --> 00:32:27.040
So I'm going to put goggles on.

00:32:27.040 --> 00:32:29.710
And those of you in the
front row have got goggles.

00:32:29.710 --> 00:32:31.840
I think, yeah, front
and second row.

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:33.340
We may get some
flakes flying off.

00:32:33.340 --> 00:32:35.400
So let's just be
careful about it.

00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:39.250
So Antony and Nada are going
to start making stone tools.

00:32:39.250 --> 00:32:41.560
And they do it by
bashing rocks together.

00:32:41.560 --> 00:32:43.660
It's actually quite
complicated, isn't it?

00:32:43.660 --> 00:32:46.057
I've had a go at doing it
and it is difficult to do it.

00:32:46.057 --> 00:32:47.140
There's quite a lot to it.

00:32:47.140 --> 00:32:47.220
Yeah--

00:32:47.220 --> 00:32:48.012
Go on then, Antony.

00:32:48.012 --> 00:32:51.850
Bash a couple of flakes
off and see what happens.

00:32:51.850 --> 00:32:54.260
And he's using a cobble
to break these flakes off.

00:32:54.260 --> 00:32:55.260
That's quite a good one.

00:32:55.260 --> 00:32:56.190
Oh, that's amazing.

00:32:56.190 --> 00:32:57.070
Look at that.

00:32:57.070 --> 00:32:59.740
As soon as you do this-- as soon
as you start breaking flakes

00:32:59.740 --> 00:33:00.250
off--

00:33:00.250 --> 00:33:02.260
you end up with things that
have got very sharp edges.

00:33:02.260 --> 00:33:03.250
It's a cutting edge.

00:33:03.250 --> 00:33:04.960
I mean, this is a stone knife.

00:33:04.960 --> 00:33:07.130
Absolutely brilliant.

00:33:07.130 --> 00:33:13.150
So you can actually see how
thin that flake is just there,

00:33:13.150 --> 00:33:15.460
especially if I shine
a light through it,

00:33:15.460 --> 00:33:18.520
you should be able to see
quite nicely that it's

00:33:18.520 --> 00:33:20.530
incredibly thin at the edges.

00:33:20.530 --> 00:33:23.330
That's a really, really
sharp cutting edge.

00:33:23.330 --> 00:33:25.990
So you'd be able to cut up your
Christmas turkey with that very

00:33:25.990 --> 00:33:27.350
easily indeed.

00:33:27.350 --> 00:33:28.920
Thank you.

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:33.380
So Antony is making
fairly basic flake tools.

00:33:33.380 --> 00:33:35.920
And over here, Nada is
making something a little bit

00:33:35.920 --> 00:33:37.540
more sophisticated,
the kind of tool

00:33:37.540 --> 00:33:39.832
that Nariokotome Boy
might have made, actually.

00:33:39.832 --> 00:33:41.290
Nada, would you
mind holding it up?

00:33:41.290 --> 00:33:42.560
Not at all.

00:33:42.560 --> 00:33:44.200
So this is a hand ax.

00:33:44.200 --> 00:33:47.170
She's making flakes which
are useful as knives,

00:33:47.170 --> 00:33:48.940
but this is useful,
too, isn't it?

00:33:48.940 --> 00:33:49.720
Yes, absolutely.

00:33:49.720 --> 00:33:50.220
Yeah.

00:33:50.220 --> 00:33:51.410
It's a multi-purpose tool.

00:33:51.410 --> 00:33:51.910
Yeah.

00:33:51.910 --> 00:33:54.190
So you could use it
for chopping, maybe;

00:33:54.190 --> 00:33:56.223
smashing bones to
get marrow out of.

00:33:56.223 --> 00:33:56.890
Absolutely, yes.

00:33:56.890 --> 00:33:57.390
Yeah.

00:33:57.390 --> 00:33:58.413
All sorts of things.

00:33:58.413 --> 00:33:59.830
The other really
interesting thing

00:33:59.830 --> 00:34:01.680
about this particular
shape is it's

00:34:01.680 --> 00:34:04.390
a shape that gets copied and
copied and copied, and passed

00:34:04.390 --> 00:34:06.490
on down through the generations.

00:34:06.490 --> 00:34:09.639
And that, I think, this tells
us something really important

00:34:09.639 --> 00:34:12.460
about the minds of
these tool makers.

00:34:12.460 --> 00:34:15.050
Because it's not just simply a
question of bashing away at it,

00:34:15.050 --> 00:34:15.550
is it.

00:34:15.550 --> 00:34:17.290
You've got a shape in your mind.

00:34:17.290 --> 00:34:19.920
No, you have to visualise what
you want to get out of a rock,

00:34:19.920 --> 00:34:21.570
and work towards that shape.

00:34:21.570 --> 00:34:22.179
Absolutely.

00:34:22.179 --> 00:34:23.560
So you are like a sculptor.

00:34:23.560 --> 00:34:25.060
You're making the shape.

00:34:25.060 --> 00:34:27.100
So that means our
ancestors, even as long ago

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:30.639
as Nariokotome Boy, were capable
of abstract thought like this.

00:34:30.639 --> 00:34:33.100
They could hold the idea
of a shape in their heads.

00:34:33.100 --> 00:34:35.110
It's quite a special
thing to be able to do.

00:34:35.110 --> 00:34:36.340
And not only that.

00:34:36.340 --> 00:34:39.280
They could make it real,
which is even more special.

00:34:39.280 --> 00:34:41.830
Thank you ever so
much Nada and Anthony.

00:34:41.830 --> 00:34:42.976
That was brilliant.

00:34:42.976 --> 00:34:43.950
Thank you.

00:34:43.950 --> 00:34:48.333
[APPLAUSE]

00:34:53.699 --> 00:34:56.500
Now stone tools
tend to stick around

00:34:56.500 --> 00:34:58.280
in the archaeological record.

00:34:58.280 --> 00:35:01.210
They're the kinds of things
that archaeologists can easily

00:35:01.210 --> 00:35:02.950
find and dig up.

00:35:02.950 --> 00:35:04.270
They're, after all, stone.

00:35:04.270 --> 00:35:06.010
It doesn't really rot away.

00:35:06.010 --> 00:35:08.860
Things we don't find
so often in archaeology

00:35:08.860 --> 00:35:11.290
are made of organic materials.

00:35:11.290 --> 00:35:15.520
So anything made out of
leaves or grass or wood

00:35:15.520 --> 00:35:17.890
is usually going to rot away.

00:35:17.890 --> 00:35:21.160
And so it's very difficult to
know exactly what our ancestors

00:35:21.160 --> 00:35:24.980
were using in terms of wooden
tools at this point in time.

00:35:24.980 --> 00:35:27.370
But we do know that
lots of hunter gatherers

00:35:27.370 --> 00:35:30.640
use very simple wooden
tools like this.

00:35:30.640 --> 00:35:33.760
And you can imagine making
this, just taking a stick,

00:35:33.760 --> 00:35:35.650
and then using one
of those stone flakes

00:35:35.650 --> 00:35:38.028
to sharpen the end of it
until you get a point.

00:35:38.028 --> 00:35:39.570
And then perhaps
what you're thinking

00:35:39.570 --> 00:35:41.070
is I'm going to use
that as a spear.

00:35:41.070 --> 00:35:42.250
Well, I could.

00:35:42.250 --> 00:35:45.130
But actually, you can use it
for something else as well--

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:46.788
something very important.

00:35:46.788 --> 00:35:48.580
And lots of modern-day
hunter gatherers use

00:35:48.580 --> 00:35:52.780
sticks like this to dig
food out of the ground.

00:35:52.780 --> 00:35:54.670
And there's a really
important clue

00:35:54.670 --> 00:35:57.370
as to what that
underground food might

00:35:57.370 --> 00:36:01.210
be when we delve into genetics.

00:36:01.210 --> 00:36:03.250
That sounds like my part.

00:36:03.250 --> 00:36:06.190
Yeah, so we can actually learn
something very interesting

00:36:06.190 --> 00:36:08.810
about our adaptations
by looking at our genes.

00:36:08.810 --> 00:36:11.620
So in your mouth you
have spit, of course.

00:36:11.620 --> 00:36:15.580
And in your saliva there
is an enzyme called amylase

00:36:15.580 --> 00:36:18.730
that helps you digest
starch in your mouth-- start

00:36:18.730 --> 00:36:21.160
breaking down the
starch in your mouth.

00:36:21.160 --> 00:36:24.920
And the amount of amylase
you have in your saliva

00:36:24.920 --> 00:36:26.755
depends on your genes.

00:36:26.755 --> 00:36:28.630
So all of you will have
noticed that you have

00:36:28.630 --> 00:36:30.040
a little packet of crackers.

00:36:30.040 --> 00:36:32.310
So you can get your
packet of crackers out.

00:36:32.310 --> 00:36:34.255
Yeah, so you're not to
start eating them yet,

00:36:34.255 --> 00:36:36.130
because I need to tell
you what to do, first.

00:36:36.130 --> 00:36:38.790
But you can just quickly
take them out of the wrapper.

00:36:38.790 --> 00:36:39.290
OK.

00:36:39.290 --> 00:36:40.720
What I want you to
do is I want you

00:36:40.720 --> 00:36:42.387
to start chewing the
cracker, but you're

00:36:42.387 --> 00:36:43.810
not to swallow it, OK?

00:36:43.810 --> 00:36:46.540
You have to keep it in your
mouth, and keep chewing.

00:36:46.540 --> 00:36:47.170
Not yet.

00:36:47.170 --> 00:36:47.680
Not yet.

00:36:47.680 --> 00:36:49.290
It's going to get
all mushy, and it's

00:36:49.290 --> 00:36:51.010
going to get all
gooey and whatever.

00:36:51.010 --> 00:36:51.760
But that's fine.

00:36:51.760 --> 00:36:54.385
Just keep it in your mouth, and
keep chewing, chewing, chewing.

00:36:54.385 --> 00:36:57.040
And at some point the
flavour is going to change.

00:36:57.040 --> 00:37:00.520
So when the flavour changes
I want you to stand up, OK?

00:37:00.520 --> 00:37:02.140
So is everybody ready?

00:37:02.140 --> 00:37:02.770
Steady.

00:37:02.770 --> 00:37:03.550
Go.

00:37:03.550 --> 00:37:04.810
Just chew, chew, chew.

00:37:04.810 --> 00:37:06.290
Don't swallow it.

00:37:06.290 --> 00:37:09.985
And then let me know
when the flavour changes.

00:37:09.985 --> 00:37:11.320
Oh, we've got one already.

00:37:11.320 --> 00:37:13.270
Very good, now.

00:37:13.270 --> 00:37:15.280
Yeah.

00:37:15.280 --> 00:37:16.240
More.

00:37:16.240 --> 00:37:17.500
And this is totally normal.

00:37:17.500 --> 00:37:21.038
It's actually expected that
different people stand up

00:37:21.038 --> 00:37:21.830
at different times.

00:37:21.830 --> 00:37:22.622
So this is amazing.

00:37:22.622 --> 00:37:24.310
Everybody's starting
to stand up.

00:37:24.310 --> 00:37:26.770
So-- ba-ba--

00:37:26.770 --> 00:37:29.020
I'm running around the stairs.

00:37:29.020 --> 00:37:31.270
What was the flavour
change for you?

00:37:31.270 --> 00:37:31.900
Boring.

00:37:31.900 --> 00:37:32.870
Boring.

00:37:32.870 --> 00:37:33.370
OK.

00:37:33.370 --> 00:37:33.870
[LAUGHING]

00:37:33.870 --> 00:37:35.200
It changed to boring.

00:37:35.200 --> 00:37:36.700
Did it start out interesting?

00:37:36.700 --> 00:37:37.520
What did you think?

00:37:37.520 --> 00:37:38.080
Sweet?

00:37:38.080 --> 00:37:39.058
It can change to sweet.

00:37:39.058 --> 00:37:39.850
What did you think?

00:37:39.850 --> 00:37:40.390
Sweet.

00:37:40.390 --> 00:37:41.140
Interesting.

00:37:41.140 --> 00:37:42.730
This is very good.

00:37:42.730 --> 00:37:44.080
What did you think?

00:37:44.080 --> 00:37:45.010
Did it change for you?

00:37:45.010 --> 00:37:46.617
It got sweeter.

00:37:46.617 --> 00:37:48.700
It's interesting that we
have people saying sweet,

00:37:48.700 --> 00:37:50.140
because that's what I expected.

00:37:50.140 --> 00:37:54.220
So the amylase enzyme in
your saliva, what it does

00:37:54.220 --> 00:37:57.070
is it breaks the starch
down into simple sugars.

00:37:57.070 --> 00:37:58.600
So it's what we
expect is that it

00:37:58.600 --> 00:38:00.980
starts to feel sweet for you.

00:38:00.980 --> 00:38:04.450
And the reason different people
stood up at different times

00:38:04.450 --> 00:38:06.580
is because actually
we know that humans

00:38:06.580 --> 00:38:09.040
have different numbers of
copies of this gene that

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:09.890
makes the amylase.

00:38:09.890 --> 00:38:11.770
So some people have two copies.

00:38:11.770 --> 00:38:14.998
But some people have as many
as 18 copies of this gene.

00:38:14.998 --> 00:38:16.540
So if you've more
copies of the gene,

00:38:16.540 --> 00:38:20.320
we expect that the flavour
would change to sweet sooner.

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:24.820
And in parts of the world where
there is a traditional diet

00:38:24.820 --> 00:38:26.380
that's very starch-rich--

00:38:26.380 --> 00:38:29.590
so things like rice
and potatoes and yams--

00:38:29.590 --> 00:38:31.960
we see that people who come
from that part of the world

00:38:31.960 --> 00:38:34.430
tend to have more copies
of the amylase gene.

00:38:34.430 --> 00:38:40.290
So it's an adaptation to diet
that's written in our genes.

00:38:40.290 --> 00:38:42.060
Yes, but our ancient
ancestors also

00:38:42.060 --> 00:38:45.544
had another way of unlocking
the energy from their food.

00:38:45.544 --> 00:38:46.044
[POOF]

00:38:46.044 --> 00:38:48.970
Woo!

00:38:48.970 --> 00:38:54.700
By a million years ago, our
ancestors had controlled fire.

00:38:54.700 --> 00:38:57.790
And with fire, they could
do all sorts of things.

00:38:57.790 --> 00:39:01.120
They could, obviously,
keep themselves warm.

00:39:01.120 --> 00:39:03.547
They could ward off predators.

00:39:03.547 --> 00:39:05.380
And they could do
something really important

00:39:05.380 --> 00:39:06.700
when it came to food.

00:39:06.700 --> 00:39:08.260
They could cook it.

00:39:08.260 --> 00:39:11.830
So things start to taste
a bit nicer, perhaps.

00:39:11.830 --> 00:39:16.030
But even more importantly,
if you can cook food,

00:39:16.030 --> 00:39:18.820
then it means you're
doing some of the work

00:39:18.820 --> 00:39:21.310
in unlocking the
energy from that food

00:39:21.310 --> 00:39:23.650
before you get it
anywhere near your mouth.

00:39:23.650 --> 00:39:27.660
So you're effectively getting
more energy from your food.

00:39:27.660 --> 00:39:29.800
And we think that
this is reflected

00:39:29.800 --> 00:39:34.090
in a change in our
ancestors' anatomy.

00:39:34.090 --> 00:39:38.580
So over time, what happened
is that our ancestors--

00:39:38.580 --> 00:39:39.820
thank you very much--

00:39:39.820 --> 00:39:43.600
who started off with
teeth as big as this--

00:39:43.600 --> 00:39:49.690
huge gnashers-- over time,
those teeth diminished in size,

00:39:49.690 --> 00:39:52.720
and got a lot more like
the teeth in your mouth.

00:39:52.720 --> 00:39:55.750
So modern human teeth
are tiny in comparison

00:39:55.750 --> 00:39:59.270
to this Australopithecine
jaw, with its teeth.

00:39:59.270 --> 00:40:01.210
So if you can make
your food softer,

00:40:01.210 --> 00:40:02.520
you can do that by pounding it.

00:40:02.520 --> 00:40:04.120
You could do it by cooking it.

00:40:04.120 --> 00:40:06.550
It means there's no longer
any advantage in having

00:40:06.550 --> 00:40:08.500
great big teeth like this.

00:40:08.500 --> 00:40:10.280
And your teeth can grow smaller.

00:40:10.280 --> 00:40:12.490
And then something
else that happens

00:40:12.490 --> 00:40:14.890
is that brains are
getting larger.

00:40:14.890 --> 00:40:16.390
And if I compare
these two skulls

00:40:16.390 --> 00:40:18.670
by showing you the
skulls like that,

00:40:18.670 --> 00:40:22.720
you can see that this modern
human skull is much bigger

00:40:22.720 --> 00:40:23.710
compared to this one.

00:40:23.710 --> 00:40:26.860
The brain cavity-- especially at
the front just above the eyes--

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:28.960
is much, much bigger.

00:40:28.960 --> 00:40:31.870
Now the brain is a
really important organ.

00:40:31.870 --> 00:40:34.660
And making a change
to a brain is

00:40:34.660 --> 00:40:37.600
something that's
quite difficult to do,

00:40:37.600 --> 00:40:40.090
as we can see from genetics.

00:40:40.090 --> 00:40:41.510
Yes, we do.

00:40:41.510 --> 00:40:44.110
And so there's something
really, really amazing

00:40:44.110 --> 00:40:47.260
that we can do with DNA
sequence analysis, which

00:40:47.260 --> 00:40:51.070
allows us to actually figure out
which are the important genes.

00:40:51.070 --> 00:40:55.120
And so to explain this to you,
I am going to tell you a story.

00:40:55.120 --> 00:40:56.350
And it's a true story.

00:40:56.350 --> 00:40:58.960
And it takes place
in World War II.

00:40:58.960 --> 00:41:01.840
So the Air Force wanted
to reinforce their planes.

00:41:01.840 --> 00:41:03.640
So they had this
idea that they would

00:41:03.640 --> 00:41:05.740
reinforce the parts
of the planes that

00:41:05.740 --> 00:41:07.270
get lots of bullet holes.

00:41:07.270 --> 00:41:09.228
So they brought in a
statistician to help them.

00:41:09.228 --> 00:41:10.937
They wanted him to
count the bullet holes

00:41:10.937 --> 00:41:12.290
and figure out where they are.

00:41:12.290 --> 00:41:13.900
But in order to picture
this, and to figure

00:41:13.900 --> 00:41:16.480
what kind of challenge this was,
we're going to do something.

00:41:16.480 --> 00:41:19.930
So you all have paper
airplanes under your seat.

00:41:19.930 --> 00:41:20.680
So just take them.

00:41:20.680 --> 00:41:22.840
Don't do anything with them yet.

00:41:22.840 --> 00:41:23.940
OK.

00:41:23.940 --> 00:41:25.690
So if you just take a
quick look at those,

00:41:25.690 --> 00:41:27.730
you'll see that they have
holes punched in them.

00:41:27.730 --> 00:41:29.770
So that's like a bullet hole.

00:41:29.770 --> 00:41:33.130
And so what I want you to do,
when I give you the word--

00:41:33.130 --> 00:41:34.450
don't anybody go early--

00:41:34.450 --> 00:41:36.182
I want you to throw
those airplanes.

00:41:36.182 --> 00:41:37.390
And I want you to aim for me.

00:41:37.390 --> 00:41:38.050
Not yet.

00:41:38.050 --> 00:41:38.902
Not yet, please!

00:41:38.902 --> 00:41:40.860
I want you to aim for
me, because basically I'm

00:41:40.860 --> 00:41:42.100
on home base, OK?

00:41:42.100 --> 00:41:43.720
Are you ready?

00:41:43.720 --> 00:41:45.130
Steady?

00:41:45.130 --> 00:41:45.997
Go.

00:41:45.997 --> 00:41:47.945
[SHRIEK]

00:41:47.945 --> 00:41:49.893
[LAUGHS]

00:41:49.893 --> 00:41:51.341
[APPLAUSE]

00:41:51.341 --> 00:41:51.841
OK!

00:41:55.260 --> 00:41:56.530
Well, that worked.

00:41:56.530 --> 00:41:57.030
OK.

00:41:57.030 --> 00:41:59.100
So the job the
statistician had then,

00:41:59.100 --> 00:42:01.800
these are all the planes that
made it back to home base.

00:42:01.800 --> 00:42:03.420
And he wanted to look at these.

00:42:03.420 --> 00:42:04.382
So I need to mark--

00:42:04.382 --> 00:42:06.090
I need to keep track
of what's happening.

00:42:06.090 --> 00:42:06.450
OK.

00:42:06.450 --> 00:42:07.500
I'll mark them on this.

00:42:07.500 --> 00:42:09.333
Alice, you could give
me a little hand here.

00:42:09.333 --> 00:42:11.318
So this one has a
bullet hole there.

00:42:11.318 --> 00:42:12.610
So you could take that from me.

00:42:12.610 --> 00:42:13.110
Yeah.

00:42:13.110 --> 00:42:15.450
And what I'm going to
do is I'm going to make

00:42:15.450 --> 00:42:17.255
little marks on this plane.

00:42:17.255 --> 00:42:18.130
So there's one there.

00:42:18.130 --> 00:42:19.380
Yeah, there's one on the wing.

00:42:19.380 --> 00:42:22.097
One on that little
bit of the wing.

00:42:22.097 --> 00:42:23.430
There's one on that bit of wing.

00:42:23.430 --> 00:42:23.880
I'll do it.

00:42:23.880 --> 00:42:24.210
OK.

00:42:24.210 --> 00:42:25.510
This is going to take forever.

00:42:25.510 --> 00:42:27.240
We need a bigger plane.

00:42:27.240 --> 00:42:28.790
Thank you.

00:42:28.790 --> 00:42:29.640
OK.

00:42:29.640 --> 00:42:32.920
So this plane we've already
collected all these data.

00:42:32.920 --> 00:42:35.120
So this is what the
statistician had to do.

00:42:35.120 --> 00:42:36.840
He had to collect
the information

00:42:36.840 --> 00:42:38.850
from all the different
planes that came back,

00:42:38.850 --> 00:42:42.750
and he mapped them onto
a picture of the plane.

00:42:42.750 --> 00:42:47.220
And the legend is that the
Air Force's first instinct

00:42:47.220 --> 00:42:48.935
was, well, we're
going to patch up

00:42:48.935 --> 00:42:50.310
those bits of the
plane that have

00:42:50.310 --> 00:42:52.180
loads of bullet holes in them.

00:42:52.180 --> 00:42:54.940
But the statistician said to
them, no, you've got it wrong,

00:42:54.940 --> 00:42:55.440
really.

00:42:55.440 --> 00:42:57.450
Because actually we
notice these parts

00:42:57.450 --> 00:43:00.240
of the plane that have
no bullet holes in them.

00:43:00.240 --> 00:43:01.710
So what's happening there?

00:43:01.710 --> 00:43:04.350
Well, they're the planes
that didn't come home.

00:43:04.350 --> 00:43:06.750
They're the ones that
had really bad damage

00:43:06.750 --> 00:43:07.920
they couldn't fly with.

00:43:07.920 --> 00:43:10.410
These are the bullet holes
that allowed the plane

00:43:10.410 --> 00:43:13.740
to fly despite the damage.

00:43:13.740 --> 00:43:17.460
So these parts of the plane
are things like the engine,

00:43:17.460 --> 00:43:20.610
or the cockpit, or
the steering gear.

00:43:20.610 --> 00:43:22.870
So by looking at the
pattern of bullet holes,

00:43:22.870 --> 00:43:27.310
you can see the important parts
and the less important parts.

00:43:27.310 --> 00:43:30.610
And it turns out we can do
this same kind of analysis

00:43:30.610 --> 00:43:31.760
with gene sequences.

00:43:31.760 --> 00:43:35.680
So if you imagine for a
moment that this is a genome,

00:43:35.680 --> 00:43:39.070
then we have some genes in the
genome where lots of mutations

00:43:39.070 --> 00:43:40.000
happen.

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:43.030
So the DNA changes, but
it doesn't really matter.

00:43:43.030 --> 00:43:45.730
So there's a change, but it's
not a significant change.

00:43:45.730 --> 00:43:48.520
And then there are other parts
of the genome-- other genes--

00:43:48.520 --> 00:43:49.960
that they really matter.

00:43:49.960 --> 00:43:52.090
And when you get
a change in them,

00:43:52.090 --> 00:43:53.830
it really affects
the individual.

00:43:53.830 --> 00:43:56.660
So they can't survive
and thrive as well.

00:43:56.660 --> 00:43:58.660
And if we look across
mammals, and we say, well,

00:43:58.660 --> 00:44:01.880
which are the genes in these
really important areas,

00:44:01.880 --> 00:44:04.510
we find that there's especially,
in these parts of the genome,

00:44:04.510 --> 00:44:08.230
it's especially genes that
are involved in your brain.

00:44:08.230 --> 00:44:10.660
So genes that work
in your brain.

00:44:10.660 --> 00:44:14.620
But something really
changed in human evolution.

00:44:14.620 --> 00:44:15.970
Woo!

00:44:15.970 --> 00:44:20.260
So in early human
evolution, these brain genes

00:44:20.260 --> 00:44:21.940
started changing quicker.

00:44:21.940 --> 00:44:23.920
They started evolving faster.

00:44:23.920 --> 00:44:26.710
So this is a really
unusual pattern.

00:44:26.710 --> 00:44:30.250
And this tells us that something
was driving that change.

00:44:30.250 --> 00:44:34.370
Something really
important had happened.

00:44:34.370 --> 00:44:37.340
So in order for these
mutations to start

00:44:37.340 --> 00:44:39.740
appearing, and then
building up and creating

00:44:39.740 --> 00:44:42.050
this big difference in
brains, and getting brains

00:44:42.050 --> 00:44:47.030
to grow larger, there must have
been a significant advantage

00:44:47.030 --> 00:44:49.130
in growing a bigger brain.

00:44:49.130 --> 00:44:51.140
And anthropologists have
wrapped their brains

00:44:51.140 --> 00:44:53.480
about what that
could possibly be

00:44:53.480 --> 00:44:55.460
that was driving this
increase in brain

00:44:55.460 --> 00:44:56.660
size in human evolution.

00:44:56.660 --> 00:45:00.380
They said, well, our ancestors
must have been working together

00:45:00.380 --> 00:45:03.530
in teams on the African
plains as hunters.

00:45:03.530 --> 00:45:05.120
So maybe it's
co-operative hunting.

00:45:05.120 --> 00:45:08.120
Maybe that's what's driving
this increase in brain size.

00:45:08.120 --> 00:45:10.370
But then hunting
dogs and lions are

00:45:10.370 --> 00:45:13.070
great at cooperating in hunting.

00:45:13.070 --> 00:45:15.050
And their brains
aren't very big at all.

00:45:15.050 --> 00:45:17.180
So then anthropologists
said, well, maybe there's

00:45:17.180 --> 00:45:17.805
something else.

00:45:17.805 --> 00:45:19.340
Maybe it's stone tools.

00:45:19.340 --> 00:45:21.560
Maybe you need a really
big brain in order

00:45:21.560 --> 00:45:23.540
to be able to make stone tools.

00:45:23.540 --> 00:45:26.660
But actually, that turns
out not to be likely either,

00:45:26.660 --> 00:45:29.530
because our ancestors started
making stone tools more

00:45:29.530 --> 00:45:32.030
than three million years ago,
when, again, their brains were

00:45:32.030 --> 00:45:33.860
pretty small.

00:45:33.860 --> 00:45:35.930
There's another group
of anthropologists

00:45:35.930 --> 00:45:39.020
who think they've got a
hypothesis which stacks up

00:45:39.020 --> 00:45:40.480
when it comes to brain size.

00:45:40.480 --> 00:45:42.650
And I need a
volunteer now to help

00:45:42.650 --> 00:45:44.837
