Thank you.

00:51:24.436 --> 00:51:26.700
It took a while to get
into Europe, didn't it?

00:51:26.700 --> 00:51:27.200
It did.

00:51:27.200 --> 00:51:28.908
There was a little
bit of hanging around.

00:51:28.908 --> 00:51:33.530
I think they might have met
some friends around here.

00:51:33.530 --> 00:51:35.150
Indigenous European people?

00:51:35.150 --> 00:51:39.140
Well, these earlier
humans who were already

00:51:39.140 --> 00:51:41.780
there before the modern
humans got there--

00:51:41.780 --> 00:51:43.100
Neanderthals.

00:51:43.100 --> 00:51:45.740
So the Neanderthals were
the inhabitants of Europe

00:51:45.740 --> 00:51:48.640
before our lot got there.

00:51:48.640 --> 00:51:51.620
And we used to think they
were entirely separate.

00:51:51.620 --> 00:51:54.650
Looking at their bones, we
thought that there was never

00:51:54.650 --> 00:51:57.020
any kind of real interaction
between modern humans

00:51:57.020 --> 00:51:57.980
and Neanderthals.

00:51:57.980 --> 00:51:59.450
But genetics has
changed all that.

00:51:59.450 --> 00:52:00.020
Yes.

00:52:00.020 --> 00:52:03.470
So what we can do now, we
can actually get DNA out

00:52:03.470 --> 00:52:04.670
of these really old bones.

00:52:04.670 --> 00:52:07.970
So we've been able to get
DNA out of Neanderthal bones.

00:52:07.970 --> 00:52:10.850
And this revealed some
really interesting surprises,

00:52:10.850 --> 00:52:13.040
because when we looked
at the Neanderthal DNA,

00:52:13.040 --> 00:52:15.320
you could see that it
didn't look actually totally

00:52:15.320 --> 00:52:17.330
different from human DNA.

00:52:17.330 --> 00:52:20.555
So, as you know, you got half
your DNA from your mum and half

00:52:20.555 --> 00:52:21.430
from your dad, right?

00:52:21.430 --> 00:52:22.220
So 50-50.

00:52:22.220 --> 00:52:25.070
And then you've got
about 25% of your DNA

00:52:25.070 --> 00:52:26.720
from each of your grandparents.

00:52:26.720 --> 00:52:29.780
And then different amounts
from other ancestors.

00:52:29.780 --> 00:52:31.820
And when we look
at people today,

00:52:31.820 --> 00:52:33.950
we find we have
chunks of DNA that are

00:52:33.950 --> 00:52:35.930
from a Neanderthal ancestor.

00:52:35.930 --> 00:52:37.220
I've got a bit in my DNA.

00:52:37.220 --> 00:52:37.790
Yeah, me too.

00:52:37.790 --> 00:52:38.540
Yeah, we all have.

00:52:38.540 --> 00:52:40.310
There's only one way
to get a chunk of DNA

00:52:40.310 --> 00:52:41.180
from somebody else.

00:52:41.180 --> 00:52:41.680
Yeah.

00:52:41.680 --> 00:52:42.340
Shenanigans.

00:52:42.340 --> 00:52:43.010
Shenanigans.

00:52:43.010 --> 00:52:44.420
Something went on.

00:52:44.420 --> 00:52:46.010
There was some
serious interaction

00:52:46.010 --> 00:52:47.710
between modern humans
and Neanderthals.

00:52:47.710 --> 00:52:48.877
You're shocking the parents.

00:52:48.877 --> 00:52:50.590
[GASP]

00:52:50.590 --> 00:52:51.930
And it's not just Neanderthals.

00:52:51.930 --> 00:52:52.430
No.

00:52:52.430 --> 00:52:56.120
There's these other species who
were around over here in Asia.

00:52:56.120 --> 00:52:58.160
And we met up with them as well.

00:52:58.160 --> 00:52:59.330
Well, they may be a species.

00:52:59.330 --> 00:53:02.420
They may just be a slightly
different set of people there.

00:53:02.420 --> 00:53:04.800
I call them Denisovans.

00:53:04.800 --> 00:53:07.010
My view is that they're
the same species,

00:53:07.010 --> 00:53:09.980
and we're all the same species,
because of all this mixing.

00:53:09.980 --> 00:53:10.540
Do you think?

00:53:10.540 --> 00:53:11.040
Yeah.

00:53:11.040 --> 00:53:12.440
That's something we disagree on.

00:53:12.440 --> 00:53:13.520
That is something
we disagree on.

00:53:13.520 --> 00:53:14.060
I'd say from the
bones, Neanderthals

00:53:14.060 --> 00:53:15.530
are different species,
but genetically

00:53:15.530 --> 00:53:16.890
you're saying they're the same.

00:53:16.890 --> 00:53:18.890
See, scientists
don't always agree.

00:53:18.890 --> 00:53:19.760
No.

00:53:19.760 --> 00:53:22.460
But with the Denisovans, there's
so little you can say, anyway.

00:53:22.460 --> 00:53:24.640
There's so little
in terms of bones--

00:53:24.640 --> 00:53:27.230
a finger bone and
three teeth, I think.

00:53:27.230 --> 00:53:29.120
But when we can get
really good DNA,

00:53:29.120 --> 00:53:31.490
actually, even though
it was just a tiny bone,

00:53:31.490 --> 00:53:33.790
the DNA inside it was really,
really well preserved.

00:53:33.790 --> 00:53:36.027
And so it's really
good DNA sequence.

00:53:36.027 --> 00:53:38.360
And if we look at people--
especially people from around

00:53:38.360 --> 00:53:39.540
this part of the world--

00:53:39.540 --> 00:53:42.860
we see that they have chunks
of DNA from Denisovans.

00:53:42.860 --> 00:53:45.360
But we've got quite a lot of
Neanderthal DNA hanging around,

00:53:45.360 --> 00:53:45.860
don't we?

00:53:45.860 --> 00:53:46.880
Yeah, yeah.

00:53:46.880 --> 00:53:49.370
So we all have chunks
of Neanderthal DNA.

00:53:49.370 --> 00:53:51.000
But we have different
chunks of DNA.

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:53.450
So if I was to take all
the different chunks

00:53:53.450 --> 00:53:56.660
and tile them together,
we get about 70%

00:53:56.660 --> 00:54:01.260
of the Neanderthal genome is
in people walking around today.

00:54:01.260 --> 00:54:03.170
I could do better
than that, Aoife.

00:54:03.170 --> 00:54:06.260
I can show you a
whole Neanderthal.

00:54:06.260 --> 00:54:07.210
[LAUGHS]

00:54:07.210 --> 00:54:10.535
[APPLAUSE]

00:54:15.300 --> 00:54:18.780
So with the help of some
quite amazing prosthetics,

00:54:18.780 --> 00:54:21.780
we have transformed
a modern human

00:54:21.780 --> 00:54:24.150
into an ancient Neanderthal.

00:54:24.150 --> 00:54:27.360
And we can see that there are
differences in the face shape.

00:54:27.360 --> 00:54:32.070
She's got a very big brow ridge
compared with us modern humans.

00:54:32.070 --> 00:54:34.710
And actually, she has a lump
at the back of her skull

00:54:34.710 --> 00:54:37.230
as well, which you can't
see under all this hair.

00:54:37.230 --> 00:54:39.450
But the skull shape's
also a different shape

00:54:39.450 --> 00:54:43.710
to ours, too, a bit long and low
compared with our more globular

00:54:43.710 --> 00:54:45.720
face shapes, or head shapes.

00:54:45.720 --> 00:54:48.450
She's got a very chunky jaw.

00:54:48.450 --> 00:54:51.507
But actually, she looks
similar enough to us

00:54:51.507 --> 00:54:54.090
that I don't think you'd really
notice if she was walking down

00:54:54.090 --> 00:54:55.590
the street, would you?

00:54:55.590 --> 00:54:57.480
And we keep on
finding more clues

00:54:57.480 --> 00:55:01.130
that Neanderthals were more like
modern humans than we thought.

00:55:01.130 --> 00:55:04.380
And one of these clues is in
what she's holding in her hand.

00:55:04.380 --> 00:55:06.360
So this is a shell.

00:55:06.360 --> 00:55:07.860
And it's a replica
based on one that

00:55:07.860 --> 00:55:10.140
was dug out of a cave in Spain.

00:55:10.140 --> 00:55:12.510
And it's a scallop shell
that's been pierced.

00:55:12.510 --> 00:55:15.030
So perhaps used as a pendant.

00:55:15.030 --> 00:55:17.940
And also painted with red ocher.

00:55:17.940 --> 00:55:21.660
So it seems that Neanderthals
were interested in decoration

00:55:21.660 --> 00:55:25.170
and art in the way that we know
our own modern human ancestors

00:55:25.170 --> 00:55:26.540
were as well.

00:55:26.540 --> 00:55:29.910
So perhaps a lot similar to us
than we previously expected.

00:55:29.910 --> 00:55:31.410
Anthropologists for
a long time have

00:55:31.410 --> 00:55:35.450
wondered whether Neanderthals
had language like we do.

00:55:35.450 --> 00:55:37.200
And that's something
we may not ever know.

00:55:37.200 --> 00:55:38.700
I mean, can you speak?

00:55:38.700 --> 00:55:40.476
Of course I can speak!

00:55:40.476 --> 00:55:41.330
[LAUGHS]

00:55:41.330 --> 00:55:43.472
We've solved the riddle.

00:55:43.472 --> 00:55:44.414
Thank you.

00:55:48.190 --> 00:55:51.170
Although Neanderthals have
left a little bit of themselves

00:55:51.170 --> 00:55:54.530
behind, and still alive in the
form of fragments of their DNA

00:55:54.530 --> 00:55:57.350
in our genomes, as
a group of people,

00:55:57.350 --> 00:56:00.110
they had died out
by 20,000 years ago.

00:56:00.110 --> 00:56:03.350
We don't find their
fossils any more.

00:56:03.350 --> 00:56:06.170
But modern humans
survived through the peak

00:56:06.170 --> 00:56:08.120
of the last ice age,
when the ice sheets

00:56:08.120 --> 00:56:12.240
descended over Northern
Europe, and over North America.

00:56:12.240 --> 00:56:14.120
And it's at this
particular time that we see

00:56:14.120 --> 00:56:17.750
an amazing explosion in art.

00:56:17.750 --> 00:56:21.080
We see our ancestors making
fantastic sculptures out

00:56:21.080 --> 00:56:22.870
of bone and ivory.

00:56:22.870 --> 00:56:26.960
And they also painted the
caves that they lived in.

00:56:26.960 --> 00:56:30.980
And here's a wonderful
painting of an ancient human

00:56:30.980 --> 00:56:33.650
in a cave painting
some of the animals

00:56:33.650 --> 00:56:35.620
that are in her environment.

00:56:35.620 --> 00:56:37.753
And there's a child
holding a lamp there,

00:56:37.753 --> 00:56:39.170
which has probably
got some animal

00:56:39.170 --> 00:56:44.300
fat in it burning away so that
she can see what she's doing.

00:56:44.300 --> 00:56:46.670
And you might think that
this seems really frivolous,

00:56:46.670 --> 00:56:49.760
that these are people surviving
through the depths of the ice

00:56:49.760 --> 00:56:50.660
age.

00:56:50.660 --> 00:56:53.180
And shouldn't they be
out hunting and gathering

00:56:53.180 --> 00:56:55.070
and keeping their
families alive?

00:56:55.070 --> 00:56:59.270
What are they doing painting
caves and making art?

00:56:59.270 --> 00:57:00.890
But it's not frivolous.

00:57:00.890 --> 00:57:03.230
Art is a really
important part of the way

00:57:03.230 --> 00:57:05.330
that we communicate
with each other.

00:57:05.330 --> 00:57:10.100
And this really underpins
our success as a species.

00:57:10.100 --> 00:57:11.480
We carry on expanding.

00:57:11.480 --> 00:57:14.420
We carry on making culture.

00:57:14.420 --> 00:57:16.940
And what we see
from the genetics

00:57:16.940 --> 00:57:18.800
is that throughout
our history we've

00:57:18.800 --> 00:57:22.340
been moving and mixing
with archaic humans,

00:57:22.340 --> 00:57:24.110
and with modern humans.

00:57:24.110 --> 00:57:26.450
And we see this
continuing today.

00:57:26.450 --> 00:57:28.970
The ethnic groups and the
populations that we recognise

00:57:28.970 --> 00:57:32.330
today are just a mix of
lots and lots of people.

00:57:32.330 --> 00:57:34.310
In the third
lecture, we're going

00:57:34.310 --> 00:57:37.790
to look at human
diversity today.

00:57:37.790 --> 00:57:41.480
And we're going to find out
how those ancient migrations

00:57:41.480 --> 00:57:45.270
contributed to the patterns
that we see around us today.

00:57:45.270 --> 00:57:49.460
And we're going to look at how
our DNA influences who we are.

00:57:49.460 --> 00:57:52.700
But for now, we're going
to close this lecture

00:57:52.700 --> 00:57:57.620
with a celebration of all of
our ancient hominid ancestors,

00:57:57.620 --> 00:57:59.370
everything that
they've given us--

00:57:59.370 --> 00:58:03.680
our love of art, our language,
all of those secrets and gifts

00:58:03.680 --> 00:58:06.415
tucked away in our DNA.

00:58:06.415 --> 00:58:07.790
And we're going
to celebrate them

00:58:07.790 --> 00:58:12.245
all with a little
musical number.

00:58:12.245 --> 00:58:15.215
Da-da!

00:58:15.215 --> 00:58:17.195
You can help me here, Alice.

00:58:17.195 --> 00:58:17.700
Really?

00:58:17.700 --> 00:58:18.800
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:58:18.800 --> 00:58:19.890
I'll just leave you
in charge of one.

00:58:19.890 --> 00:58:20.180
OK.

00:58:20.180 --> 00:58:20.930
Everybody ready?

00:58:20.930 --> 00:58:22.599
See if you recognise this.

